						               													<description>The game &amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#137;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#179; (Wordon) consists of a pad of papers showing the Japanese hiragana alphabet in a grid of letters overlaid on a map of the ocean, with a coast and a few islands.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The winner of the game will be the first to sink the opponent's ships.  At the beginning of the game, the players agree on a topic, and secretly choose three words, of different lengths, corresponding to their three ships.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;On their turn, a player can either try to guess the word for one of the opponent's ships or guess a letter in their grid.  If the player guesses a letter, the opponent responds either that it was a hit, a splash, or a miss.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;A ship sinks when either the word is guessed or each of the letters used to spell the word has been &amp;quot;hit&amp;quot;.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
